node.text:
For the past few months, I have been working on creating an online offering that has the same feel and quality content of an in-person event. Together with Soren of @wisdom2events and @guynamedlindsey we have created Committed to the Journey. It is an interview series where I cover topics from relationships, unlocking creativity, healing and growth, my personal story, how inner-work impacts society, and much more. I try to keep my events accessible and this will be no different, for $20 you can access all of the interviews, which is more than 3 hours of content. You can access the videos by going to the top link in my bio or by going directly to vimeo.com/ondemand/committedtothejourney or by checking out my stories. Really excited to bring you this series; in a way this feels like the direct follow up to my first book Inward. I hope it serves you well.

Sending love to all 🙏🏽 #yungpueblo

Hey friends, a segment aired on @nightline on @abcnetwork last night featuring my work as a writer and speaker. It is surreal seeing this summary of things. I didn’t know how everything would turn out when I started sharing my writing on Instagram back in 2015. Grateful to everyone who helped along the way. Special thanks to @lauraecoburn for producing this piece and @danharris and the @tenpercenthappier team for interviewing me. Also @sacredspacemiami for letting us get footage of the event. Sending much love to all beings. #yungpueblo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by yung pueblo on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'i was never addicted to one thing, i was addicted to filling a void within myself with things other than my own love yung pueblo'.

node.text:
When sadness and anxiety took control of my actions it led me into the darkest period of my life. What started my journey inward was a pain and tension that had become so loud within me that it started pouring out into my life as destructive behavior. I hurt myself the most when I fell into a constant hunt for pleasure, not realizing that I was actually seeking love and the inner peace that comes with happiness. Unprepared and unwilling to see what was inside of me, I found pleasure to be my great escape, this led me into using drugs to the point where I became incredibly unhealthy in my body, mind and relationships.

Never being able to find satisfaction in the sensation of pleasure, the downward spiral into misery eventually shifted when my body said enough. I felt so sick and out of balance that my life felt like it was drifting away. Realizing that I was on the edge, it hit me that I could still turn everything around and that I had the power to start moving in a different direction. The first instance of reclaiming my power was when I said no more to hard drugs and started saying yes to being radically honest with myself.

In the summer of 2011, I began to change my habits by focusing on healing my body through nutrition, exercise and by engaging with my inner turmoil through moving inward with honesty, compassion and courage. This helped me accept how miserable I was and how rebirth was possible. Slowly the new habits made me feel stronger, calmer and gentler with my own life and the lives of those around me. Starting to have love for myself showed me how similar we all are. In the summer of 2012 the deep healing started when I did my first silent 10 day Vipassana course, which helped me begin the process of releasing the patterns that limit my happiness and freedom.

My personal history has shown me one critically important truth: real healing is possible, but it does take courage and effort to build the habits that can create a new life. I am not fully free, there is much more to release, but I'm grateful to be here and on my way. Sending love to all beings. May we all be happy and free. 🙏🏽🌎 #yungpueblo

node.text:
Peace is not passive, it is mental clarity and compassion in action. Your healing not only benefits you and everyone you encounter, but it helps you make better and more humane decisions in a rapidly changing world.

Personal healing is important, but collective healing is also critical. Human beings do not live in a vacuum, our interconnectedness is what gives us the opportunity to thrive. It definitely helps the world when we heal ourselves, but we should also find ways to do our part to support movements for a better and more just world. When people move together around a common cause, history changes.

It is easy to recreate the harm that has happened to us if we never take the time to process it in a healthy way. This is why your healing is a gift to the people who will cross your path in the future.

The same way it is to your personal benefit to not harm others, it is also to your personal benefit for others to be safe from harm and have their material needs met. When more people can truly flourish, the shared happiness of humanity will also increase.

The mental clarity that comes after healing helps us engage more deeply with complexity, which is what we need to understand the issues in front of us so we can substantially decrease direct and indirect forms of harm.

Sending love to all. 🙏🏽🌎 #yungpueblo

node.text:
Letting go is not a one time event, it is a habit that requires consistent repetition to become strong. Sometimes the reaction to the pain is so deep that you will have to observe and release the tension repeatedly to fully cleanse the wound.

Letting go reaches its highest levels when your observation of what is happening inside of you is done with total acceptance. Especially in the mind, adding more tension to the tension that is already there will not make things better. When tension is met with unconditional acceptance, it has the space it needs to naturally unfold and release.

Letting go always seems opaque in the beginning, there is no one way to do it. There are many techniques out there. I personally practice Vipassana meditation and it has helped me tremendously, but I have friends who have had great success in other forms of meditation, journaling, and 1 on 1 therapy.

There is so much out there, what matters is finding something that meets your conditioning where it is at. Something that is challenging but not overwhelming. If you are open to it, please share what has helped you let go in the comments. It is helpful for all of us to see what is working for other people.

Unloading the mental weight of past hurt is never easy, but it is possible, especially when we feel ready for a great transformation.

Sending love to all 🙏🏽🌎 #yungpueblo
